      "text": "Existing Arabic resources are often small in scale such as QAES (Bashendy et al., 2024), lack trait-specific annotations as in ZAEBAC (Habash and Palfreyman, 2022), or consist solely of unannotated essays such as ALC."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q12",
      "page": 2,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "Table 2: Comparison of LAILA with existing essay datasets. \"Len\" is average essay length in words; \"HOL\" indicates holistic scoring; \"Eur\" covers German, Italian, and Czech; \"L1/L2\" denotes native or second-language learners; \"Public\" here means freely available."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q13",
      "page": 2,
      "dimension": "output_ontology",
      "text": "tailed trait-specific annotations that capture multiple dimensions of writing proficiency."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q14",
      "page": 2,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "We establish baseline AES results for Arabic under two evaluation setups: prompt-specific and cross-prompt."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q15",
      "page": 2,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "We publicly release LAILA, including essays with holistic and trait-specific annotations. We also release the benchmarking code to support replication and future research."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q16",
      "page": 2,
      "dimension": "input_content",
      "text": "Section 2 reviews related work and existing AES datasets. Section 3 outlines the data collection design principles, while Section 4 describes the dataset construction process, including school and prompt selection, essay collection, and annotations."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q17",
      "page": 2,
      "dimension": "input_content",
      "text": "Research on AES has advanced considerably in English, supported by large-scale, publicly available datasets such as ASAP/ASAP++ (Mathias and Bhattacharyya, 2018), TOEFL11 (Blanchard et al., 2013), ELLIPSE (Crossley et al., 2023a), and PERSUADE (Crossley et al., 2023b)."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q18",
      "page": 2,
      "dimension": "input_content",
      "text": "In contrast, other languages have far fewer resources. Some smaller datasets exist, including ACEA (Chinese; annotated but not public) (He et al., 2022), TCFLE-8 (French; public but with only holistic scores) (Wilkens et al., 2023), and MERLIN (German, Italian, and Czech; public but limited to holistic annotations) (Boyd et al., 2014). While useful for AES studies, their limited scale and annotation depth restrict their utility."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q19",
      "page": 2,
      "dimension": "input_content",
      "text": "Compared with English and other languages, Arabic AES lacks robust datasets. Few datasets have been developed, both public and proprietary, yet all face limitations in scale, annotation depth, or accessibility."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q20",
      "page": 3,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "The development of LAILA was guided by nine core design principles [D1–D9], each reflecting deliberate choices to ensure a high-quality, representative, and ethically sound resource for Arabic AES."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q21",
      "page": 3,
      "dimension": "input_content",
      "text": "[D1] Ensuring Data Integrity: We designed LAILA to capture authentic, classroom-produced writing created without external assistance. This design choice preserves genuine linguistic variation, learner errors, and authentic complexities essential for real-world AES applications."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q22",
      "page": 3,
      "dimension": "input_content",
      "text": "[D2] Maximizing Diversity: To reflect the breadth of Arabic writing proficiency, LAILA was planned to collect essays from multiple educational institutions and student populations with diverse academic and demographic backgrounds. Prompts were intentionally varied across genres, ensuring cultural relevance and age appropriateness, thereby promoting model generalization and reducing bias."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q23",
      "page": 3,
      "dimension": "input_content",
      "text": "[D3] Achieving Gender Balance: We intentionally aimed to balance the number of essays from male and female students to promote fairness, reduce gender-based bias, support inclusive evaluation, and enhance model generalization."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q24",
      "page": 3,
      "dimension": "output_ontology",
      "text": "[D4] Supporting Full Trait Coverage: LAILA was built to capture multiple dimensions of writing quality through annotations of relevance, organization, vocabulary, style, development, mechanics, and grammar. This design supports fine-grained assessment and meaningful feedback."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q25",
      "page": 3,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "[D5] Ensuring Authentic Writing Conditions: To emulate real academic or high-stakes testing scenarios, LAILA was designed to collect essays written under timed conditions using a digital submission platform. This setup ensures consis"
    },
    {
      "id": "Q26",
      "page": 5,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "taining one persuasive and one explanatory prompt, along with a unique, pre-generated ID to maintain students' anonymity while enabling metadata tracking [D6]. We also configured a Microsoft Form for digital essay submission, set with a 65-minute time limit to enforce a time-restricted setup [D5]."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q27",
      "page": 5,
      "dimension": "input_content",
      "text": "Data collection spanned one academic year through 27 school visits (24 initial, three follow-ups), by nine team members, to meet the target student count."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q28",
      "page": 5,
      "dimension": "input_content",
      "text": "Each visit, which lasted around six hours, was supported by at least two team members, an IT teacher, and proctoring teachers."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q29",
      "page": 5,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "The collected essays then underwent a cleaning process to ensure data quality before the annotation phase. First, we resolved duplicate and misidentified submissions, by correcting ID mismatches through manual verification and name cross-referencing. Next, a manual review eliminated submissions lacking meaningful content, e.g., irrelevant personal content. Lastly, essays with 10 or fewer words were excluded for being insufficient for AES analysis."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q30",
      "page": 5,
      "dimension": "output_content",
      "text": "The hired annotation team consisted of 6 annotators and 3 supervisors, all of whom were Arabic language teachers or lecturers with educational backgrounds."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q31",
      "page": 5,
      "dimension": "output_content",
      "text": "Five members of the team hold advanced degrees (MSc or PhD) in the Arabic language."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q32",
      "page": 5,
      "dimension": "output_content",
      "text": "The supervisors oversaw training, quality assurance, and dispute resolution, while the annotators performed the primary scoring tasks."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q33",
      "page": 5,
      "dimension": "output_ontology",
      "text": "All essays in LAILA dataset were scored using the Core Academic Skills Test (CAST) rubric [D7], developed by the Qatar University Testing Center (QUTC)."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q34",
      "page": 5,
      "dimension": "output_ontology",
      "text": "The rubric covers 7 writing traits [D4]: Relevance (REL), Organization (ORG), Vocabulary (VOC), Style (STY), Development (DEV), Mechanics (MEC), and Grammar (GRA)."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q35",
      "page": 5,
      "dimension": "output_ontology",
      "text": "Additionally, a Holistic score (HOL) was computed as the sum of the 7 trait scores."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q36",
      "page": 5,
      "dimension": "output_ontology",
      "text": "Six traits (all but REL) were rated on a 6-point scale (0 = lowest, 5 = highest), while REL was rated on a 3-point scale (0 = not relevant, 1 = partially relevant, and 2 = fully relevant)."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q37",
      "page": 5,
      "dimension": "output_ontology",
      "text": "Furthermore, if an essay received a REL score of 0, all other trait scores were set to 0, as irrelevant responses are not subject to further evaluation."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q38",
      "page": 6,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "LAILA comprises 7,859 essays collected across 8 distinct prompts: 3 explanatory and 5 persuasive (3,446 and 4,413 essays, respectively)."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q39",
      "page": 6,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "Table 3 shows that the number of essays per prompt ranges from 500 to 1,181. Essay lengths demonstrate consistency across prompts, with an average of 171 words and a maximum of 706 words."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q40",
      "page": 6,
      "dimension": "output_ontology",
      "text": "Most traits follow a near-normal pattern on the 6-point scale, indicating overall positive essay quality. The REL scores show that 86% of the essays agree strongly with the prompt. In contrast, GRA and VOC show the highest percentage of score 1 at 16%, followed by MEC at 13%, highlighting that these traits pose the greatest challenges."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q41",
      "page": 6,
      "dimension": "output_content",
      "text": "To ensure consistency, 2 supervisors developed an annotation guidebook with detailed terminology, exemplars, and annotated practices for each prompt type. Annotators were required to review these materials and complete training sessions before formal annotation. Moderation sessions followed, where discrepancies were discussed and interpretations of the rubric were harmonized."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q42",
      "page": 6,
      "dimension": "output_content",
      "text": "The scoring process was conducted using the Assessment Gourmet Platform, which supports large-scale, anonymized essay scoring. The platform ensured that annotators were blinded to student identity [D6], while only supervisors had access to annotator metadata for monitoring purposes."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q43",
      "page": 6,
      "dimension": "output_content",
      "text": "The essays were randomly distributed among the annotators to minimize systematic bias, and the scoring sessions were capped to prevent annotators' fatigue. Each essay was independently scored by two annotators across all traits. If the difference in HOL scores between the two annotators was less than 6 points, the mean of the two scores was computed and then rounded down to the nearest integer; this rounded value was adopted as the final score for each trait. However, essays with large discrepancies between annotators (≥ 6 points difference in the HOL score) were flagged and escalated to a supervisor (a third annotator in this case), who provided the final adjudicated score and offered feedback to the annotators to improve alignment and consistency in subsequent batches of essays."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q44",
      "page": 6,
      "dimension": "output_content",
      "text": "We compute IAA using Quadratic Weighted Kappa (QWK) (Williamson et al., 2012) to assess agreement between the two main annotators (A1 and A2), prior to adjudication. Table 4 reports QWK per trait and prompt, with agreement strength following Landis and Koch (1977). Overall, IAA was substantial across prompts, with an average QWK ranging from 0.66 (P5) to 0.75 (P1), showing strong consistency."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q45",
      "page": 6,
      "dimension": "output_content",
      "text": "However, variability emerges by prompt and trait. In particular, P5 showed the lowest average agreement, noting that it has the highest percentage of essays that require a third annotator (A3: 23.3%; Table 3). This suggests greater initial disagreement"
    },
    {
      "id": "Q46",
      "page": 7,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "For each setup, we investigate two research questions in the context of Arabic AES: (RQ1) how do different categories of models compare in overall performance?, and (RQ2) which models achieve the best results across individual traits?."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q47",
      "page": 7,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "Model Selection We selected a diverse set of models with varying architectures to establish strong baselines for LAILA. The selection criteria included code availability, ease of implementation, and coverage of SOTA Arabic and English models."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q48",
      "page": 7,
      "dimension": "output_ontology",
      "text": "The models fall into three categories: feature-based (FB), encoder-based, and large language models (LLMs). LLMs were evaluated in zero-shot and few-shot settings, and all models followed a multitask setup predicting holistic and trait scores jointly."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q49",
      "page": 7,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "We selected 4 FB models: Linear Regression (LR), Random Forest (RF), Extreme Gradient Boosting (XGB), and a feedforward Neural Network (NN)."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q50",
      "page": 7,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "For encoder-based models, we fine-tuned two pre-trained SOTA systems: AraBERT (Antoun et al., 2020), combined with handcrafted features (Sayed et al., 2025), and AraT5 (Nagoudi et al., 2022), inspired by the strong performance of T5 in English AES (Do et al., 2024)."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q51",
      "page": 7,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "For LLMs, we evaluated three Arabic-centric models: ALLaM (Bari et al., 2025), Command-R7B-Arabic (R7B) (Alnumay et al., 2025), and Fanar (Team et al., 2025), under zero-shot and few-shot (5-shot) settings."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q52",
      "page": 7,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "For the prompt-specific experiments, we used 5-fold cross-validation using the predefined 5 splits. In each cross-validation iteration, one fold (20%) was used as the test set, and the remaining four folds were further split into training (70%) and development (10%) sets, with stratification applied to maintain consistent prompt distributions and ensure consistent evaluation across models."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q53",
      "page": 7,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "For encoder-based models, we employ the same AraBERT-based architecture, which performed strongly in Arabic AES (Sayed et al., 2025), along with two SOTA English AES models, ProTACT (Do et al., 2023) and MOOSE (Chen et al., 2025)."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q54",
      "page": 8,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "We implemented the 816 handcrafted features introduced by Sayed et al. (2025) for Arabic AES, encompassing surface, readability, lexical, semantic, and syntactic aspects."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q55",
      "page": 8,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "These features were applied to the FB models, ProTACT, MOOSE, and AraBERT."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q56",
      "page": 8,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "To mitigate noise, we performed feature selection based on Pearson and Spearman correlations (Li and Ng, 2024), retaining features whose absolute correlation with any trait exceeded a predefined threshold for either metric."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q57",
      "page": 8,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "For MOOSE, however, we did not apply this explicit feature selection step."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q58",
      "page": 8,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "We evaluate model performance using QWK to measure agreement between human and model scores."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q59",
      "page": 8,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "Hyperparameters are tuned via Bayesian optimization with the Tree-structured Parzen Estimator algorithm (Bergstra et al., 2011), implemented using Optuna's TPESampler."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q60",
      "page": 8,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "We ran 20 trials with 5 startup trials and a fixed random seed of 11."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q61",
      "page": 8,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "The best configuration, selected based on average QWK on the development set, was used for final evaluation on the test data."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q62",
      "page": 9,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "FB models showed comparable performance, with only a 2-point difference between the top performer (XGB) and the lowest (NN), highlighting consistency of these feature-based approaches."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q63",
      "page": 9,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "Among encoder-based models, ProTACT exhibited the lowest performance overall, suggesting limited transferability from its English architecture, while AraBERT trailed XGB by 4.4 points."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q64",
      "page": 9,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "Notably, MOOSE achieved the highest performance among all evaluated cross-prompt models."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q65",
      "page": 9,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "For LLMs, few-shot prompting improved Fanar and R7B (+19 and +11.6 points), whereas ALLaM dropped by 7 points, indicating high sensitivity to prompt design."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q66",
      "page": 9,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "No single model consistently outperformed the others across individual traits."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q67",
      "page": 9,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "MOOSE performed best in REL, STY, and GRA traits."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q68",
      "page": 9,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "For the remaining traits, RF led in VOC and HOL, XGB in ORG, and Fanar (5) in DEV and MEC."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q69",
      "page": 9,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "Encoder-based models excel in prompt-specific tasks, approaching the IAA (Table 4), which indicates a close reach to the human performance."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q70",
      "page": 9,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "AraBERT exhibits the best performance overall in the prompt-specific setup with an average QWK performance of 0.74."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q71",
      "page": 9,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "However, its cross-prompt performance drops significantly (average QWK: 0.549), underscoring its ability to capture prompt-dependent patterns rather than generalizable features."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q72",
      "page": 9,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "We note that the applicability of the prompt-specific setup is relatively limited due to reliance on target prompt essays that are labeled, which is often unavailable in practice."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q73",
      "page": 9,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "In the cross-prompt setup, while MOOSE achieves the highest average performance (average QWK: 0.597), we observe that classical FB models (XGB) remain remarkably competitive."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q74",
      "page": 9,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "This confirms that handcrafted features capture prompt-independent linguistic properties that generalize better in the more challenging and realistic cross-prompt setup than some standard encoders."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q75",
      "page": 9,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "LLMs, specifically Fanar and R7B with few shots, exhibit consistent performance across both setups, indicating they capture general scoring criteria."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q76",
      "page": 9,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "Their relative underperformance in prompt-specific tasks reflects their limited ability to exploit prompt-dependent patterns without fine-tuning."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q77",
      "page": 9,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "Overall, the findings of the benchmarking experiments above highlight the need to prioritize future research on cross-prompt AES, which is practically closer to the real world, while best models are still far from human performance."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q78",
      "page": 9,
      "dimension": "input_content",
      "text": "While research on automated scoring of English essays began more than 55 years ago, Arabic essay scoring is hindered by the lack of data resources."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q79",
      "page": 9,
      "dimension": "input_content",
      "text": "To bridge this gap, this paper introduced LAILA, the first large-scale publicly available dataset for Arabic AES."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q80",
      "page": 9,
      "dimension": "input_content",
      "text": "The dataset comprises 7,859 essays written on 8 different prompts by 4,372 high school students, and provides annotations for 7 writing traits as well as a holistic score with substantial inter-annotator agreement."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q81",
      "page": 9,
      "dimension": "input_content",
      "text": "This makes it a comprehensive and reliable resource for training models and evaluating writing quality of Arabic essays."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q82",
      "page": 9,
      "dimension": "output_content",
      "text": "For reproducibility, we detailed the data collection and annotation process."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q83",
      "page": 9,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "We also benchmarked LAILA using SOTA Arabic and English AES models in both prompt-specific and cross-prompt settings, showing strong baselines for future research."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q84",
      "page": 9,
      "dimension": "output_content",
      "text": "We heartily thank our dedicated annotators for their contributions and express our gratitude to Qatar University Testing Center, the Ministry of Education and Higher Education in Qatar (the Arabic Section of the Department Of Educational Supervision in particular), participating schools, and students for making this work possible."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q85",
      "page": 9,
      "dimension": "output_content",
      "text": "We also acknowledge the support of Advanced Group for Information Technology (AGI) for providing access to the platform, Assessment Gourmet, which was used to manage and administer the annotation process."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q86",
      "page": 9,
      "dimension": "output_content",
      "text": "This work was made possible by NPRP grant NPRP14S-0402-210127 from the Qatar Research Development and Innovation (QRDI) Council."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q87",
      "page": 9,
      "dimension": "input_content",
      "text": "While LAILA represents a significant step forward for Arabic AES, it has notable limitations."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q88",
      "page": 9,
      "dimension": "input_content",
      "text": "First, LAILA was collected from students in a single country, Qatar, and specific grade levels, grades 10 to 12, which may limit its generalizability to other Arabic-speaking populations due to diverse educational systems. However, this concern is partially mitigated by Qatar's large population of Arab expatriates, resulting in student participants representing a wide variety of Arabic dialects and backgrounds."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q89",
      "page": 10,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "Second, LAILA includes only explanatory and persuasive writing prompts, limiting genre diversity and potentially affecting model robustness across other styles, such as narrative or descriptive writing."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q90",
      "page": 10,
      "dimension": "input_content",
      "text": "Third, two of the prompts (Prompts 3 and 4) have fewer essays than the rest, which could introduce imbalance and lead to skewed performance in prompt-specific evaluations."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q91",
      "page": 10,
      "dimension": "output_ontology",
      "text": "Fourth, the relevance trait is scored on a narrow scale from 0 to 2, which limits the granularity of evaluation and may cause QWK to underrepresent subtle differences in model predictions."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q92",
      "page": 10,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "Fifth, with an average essay length of only 171 words, the dataset lacks extended writing samples, restricting the assessment of models on long-form academic tasks requiring more complex, extended compositions."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q93",
      "page": 10,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "Finally, we acknowledge that the experimental results reported in Table 5 do not aim to exhaustively benchmark state-of-the-art AES models; rather, they serve as baseline performance for LAILA."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q94",
      "page": 10,
      "dimension": "input_content",
      "text": "We emphasize that the primary contribution of this work lies in the construction and public release of a large-scale Arabic AES dataset, rather than in proposing novel AES model architectures."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q95",
      "page": 10,
      "dimension": "output_content",
      "text": "The collection of LAILA received approval from an Institutional Review Board (IRB Number: QU-IRB 159/2024-EA) and was conducted with informed consent from both students and their legal guardians."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q96",
      "page": 10,
      "dimension": "input_content",
      "text": "Essays were written under exam-style supervised conditions, with participation entirely voluntary and independent of students' academic evaluations or grades."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q97",
      "page": 10,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "To protect participant privacy, all submissions were assigned pre-generated anonymous identifiers, and personally identifiable information was systematically removed during data cleaning."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q98",
      "page": 10,
      "dimension": "output_content",
      "text": "Annotation was conducted on a platform that prevented annotators from accessing student identities or demographic information."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q99",
      "page": 10,
      "dimension": "input_content",
      "text": "Essay prompts were carefully designed to be developmentally appropriate for the target age groups, culturally relevant to the Arabic-speaking context, and free of sensitive topics or potentially harmful content."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q100",
      "page": 10,
      "dimension": "input_content",
      "text": "The dataset includes balanced gender representation and covers grades 10-12."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q101",
      "page": 10,
      "dimension": "output_content",
      "text": "All annotators were qualified Arabic language educators who received fair compensation at or above local professional rates."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q102",
      "page": 10,
      "dimension": "output_content",
      "text": "They completed structured training on annotation guidelines, and inter-annotator disagreements were resolved through systematic adjudication procedures."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q103",
      "page": 10,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "The dataset will be released exclusively for research and educational purposes in Arabic automated essay scoring."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q104",
      "page": 10,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "We explicitly prohibit its use for high-stakes educational decisions affecting individual students."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q105",
      "page": 10,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "Users must commit to: (1) preventing re-identification attempts, (2) avoiding demographic profiling or inference, and (3) refraining from deployment in operational assessment contexts without independent validation."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q106",
      "page": 10,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "We recommend that any system developed using LAILA undergo fairness auditing and stakeholder consultation before real-world application."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q107",
      "page": 11,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "TAQEEM 2025: Overview of the first shared task for Arabic quality evaluation of essays in multi-dimensions."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q108",
      "page": 11,
      "dimension": "output_ontology",
      "text": "QAES: First publicly-available trait-specific annotations for automated scoring of Arabic essays."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q109",
      "page": 11,
